---
import LightLayout from '../../../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="Script · Steam" description="Structured script by blocks for Stripe Product Sense.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 pb-6">
    <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Back to hub</a>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mt-6 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">🎮</span>
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black !my-0" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Script · Steam</h1>
        <p class="!my-1 font-medium" style="color: var(--color-primary);">~7 min read aloud · marketplace + platform + social</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="prose-factory">

      <div class="card !p-5 my-6" style="background: rgba(236,72,153,0.10); border: 1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.25);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">📌 How to use this script</h3>
        <p class="!mb-0">Steam is your differentiated pick. Stripe won't hear 10 candidates talking about Steam that day. Use that advantage. The strongest piece here is <strong>the inverted 30% model</strong>: use it, it's what separates a good interview from a great one.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[USER]</h2>
      <p>"I'm going to talk about <strong>Steam</strong>, which I use daily as a gamer but also study as a three-sided system. My primary user is <strong>the adult gamer with an accumulated library</strong>, someone who's been on the platform 5+ years and has 50+ games purchased."</p>
      <p>"I'm choosing this segment because it defines the economics of Steam: it's not new gamers who sustain the platform, it's accumulated gamers who have an incentive to stay because of history, not because of current catalogue. Other users, the casual gamer, the mod creator, the indie developer, I'll touch on as contrast."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 The reason "history vs current catalogue" is the key to Steam's lock-in. This will help you later defend against Epic Games Store.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[SUB-SEGMENTS]</h2>
      <p>"Within the adult gamer with accumulated library, I distinguish three sub-segments by how they use Steam."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>The completionist.</strong> Buys games on sale, accumulates them, plays few. Steam Sales is their event of the year."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The social player.</strong> Uses Steam mainly as a client to find friends and voice chat. Community usage, not transactional."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The curator.</strong> Reads reviews, writes reviews, follows curators, checks hours-played before buying. Steam is their discovery filter."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"I'm going to focus on <strong>the curator</strong>, because it's the sub-segment where Steam has the deepest moat and where a product change has asymmetric returns."</p>

      <h2>[ECOSYSTEM]</h2>
      <p>"Steam lives on three boards simultaneously."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Games marketplace</strong>, competing with Epic Games Store, GOG, Microsoft Store, and increasingly with consoles entering PC."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Technical platform</strong>, where Steam doesn't compete, it's infrastructure. Installation, updates, cloud saves, sync across machines. This is the operating system of PC gaming, and Valve has invested in it for 20 years."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Vertical social network</strong>, competing with Discord for chat, Twitch for streaming, Reddit for community. Steam is a relative loser in each separately, but absolute winner when integrated with your library and your friends."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"Any proposal has to reinforce at least one without breaking the other two."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 3. Anchor phrase here: "Steam is the operating system of PC gaming". Repeat it; it gives you gravitas.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[THE 30% TENSION]</h2>
      <p>"Before I propose, I want to name the central tension of Steam: <strong>the 30% commission Steam charges developers</strong>. Epic Games Store entered with 12% and attacked that tension directly. The public narrative says Steam is unfair and Epic is fair. But the data isn't that simple."</p>
      <p>"The 30% pays for infrastructure, global distribution, anti-cheat, cloud, community, coordinated mass discounts, and a user history Epic can't replicate. The real question is not 'is 30% fair?', it's 'is 30% creating enough value for developers who don't have an equivalent distribution alternative?'."</p>

      <h2>[PROPOSAL]</h2>
      <p>"My proposal: <strong>an inverted commission model</strong>. Steam offers indie developers an optional tier where Steam takes 5% instead of 30%, but the developer pays for the services used (hosting, anti-cheat, cloud) as a monthly subscription, independent of revenue."</p>
      <p>"It connects to the curator (my sub-segment) because more indies would surface on Steam, and the curator is who filters that flow. It serves small developers who run on very thin margins. And it neutralises Epic's attack, because now Steam can argue transparency: 'it's not an opaque 30%, it's 5% plus billed services as SaaS, just like any cloud infrastructure'."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 This is the differentiating piece of the interview. Steam doesn't offer this today, but structurally it's defensible. You reframe the question from "commission" to "value model": that's the senior-PM move.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[EDGE CASES]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, AAA developers who reach the 30% bracket and switch to 5% paying for services. A AAA with $10M revenue would save millions. Is that desirable? Solution: the inverted model applies only to developers below 1M USD annual revenue, tiered."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, the developer who pays SaaS upfront and then doesn't sell. They lose money. Solution: free month 1, sustainability check before migrating to the model."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, communication to the end user. The curator doesn't need to know which commission model each game uses. But the developer does need a transparency page. Solution: dashboard for devs internally, invisible to the gamer."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[RISKS: TIGER + PAPER TIGER]</h2>
      <p>"<strong>🐅 Tiger:</strong> revenue erosion. If 20% of Steam's catalogue moves to the inverted model, Steam loses margin on those games. Mitigation: the inverted model is only offered to games with low absolute revenue, and the SaaS services are priced to cover target margin."</p>
      <p>"<strong>📰 Paper Tiger:</strong> 'Epic Games Store will win the war eventually with 12%'. Sounds plausible but doesn't hold against data. Epic has been at 12% for 5 years and hasn't broken past 15% PC market share. The reason isn't commission, it's <strong>accumulated infrastructure and user history</strong>. A gamer with 200 games on Steam doesn't move to Epic for 18 commission points that don't even affect them. And devs know it."</p>

      <h2>[METRICS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Target:</strong> number of active indie games on Steam, annual aggregate. North Star because it measures the effect we want, that Steam remains the primary indie destination."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Leading:</strong> adoption rate of the inverted model by new developers in the first 6 months. Target 30%."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Lagging:</strong> revenue per dev in the indie segment at 18 months. Target +15% (more viable devs = more diversity)."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Guard rail:</strong> total platform margin doesn't drop more than 5%. If it does, the inverted model is recalibrated or limited."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[TRANSPLANT]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine the interviewer says: 'OK, now do it for Steam mobile, in emerging markets'."</p>
      <p>"<strong>OK, let me pause. The context changes a lot.</strong> For Steam mobile in emerging markets, at least three assumptions break."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, I assumed PC as the primary device and games as a long-hours investment. On mobile, sessions are short, games are casual, and the real competitor isn't Epic, it's the App Store and Google Play, which already own the mobile ecosystem."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, I assumed accumulated library as a moat. On mobile, the young user has no Steam history; they're being born on the platform. The retention-by-history strategy doesn't apply, we have to build engagement from scratch."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, I assumed 30% as the central tension. On mobile, the standard commission is also 30% on App Store and Google Play, so Steam has no relative advantage. The inverted-model argument is still valid but no longer differentiating."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"With those assumptions broken, my proposal transforms. Instead of the inverted model, I'd propose <strong>cross-play integration with the same user's PC library</strong>. The adult gamer who already has 200 games on PC should be able to play compatible mobile versions without re-buying. That uses the history moat that already exists in another context, rather than inventing one from scratch on mobile."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 9 clean. And the final reformulation ("using the existing moat in another context") is the kind of strategic judgement Stripe wants to see.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[IF THEY PUSH BACK]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'the inverted model fragments the catalogue, aren't you creating two classes of games on Steam?'"</p>
      <p>"Good question. Let me distinguish two things. <strong>Visibility to the gamer</strong>, which has to be equal regardless of the model, I don't want first-class and second-class citizens on the discovery page. <strong>Monetisation model to the dev</strong>, which can vary because it's invisible to the gamer. The legitimate fragmentation happens in the backend (how the dev pays to use the platform), not in the frontend (how the gamer finds the game). My mistake in the first answer was not separating those two layers explicitly."</p>

      <hr class="my-10" />

      <div class="card !p-6 my-8" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">🎯 The three anchor sentences</h3>
        <ol class="!mb-0">
          <li><strong>"Steam is the operating system of PC gaming"</strong> (situating the platform).</li>
          <li><strong>"The difference isn't commission, it's a value model"</strong> (defending the 30%).</li>
          <li><strong>"Visibility to the gamer vs monetisation model to the dev"</strong> (the finer distinction under pressure).</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-3 mt-10">
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/google-maps" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Google Maps</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Hub</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/github" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">GitHub →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</LightLayout>
